# Loading states

While content loads, show the shared spinner — not skeleton placeholders, blank screens, or ad-hoc spinners.

## Source of truth

- Spinner: `LoadingSpinner` in `app/components/loading.tsx`
- Content-area loading: `PageLoading` in `app/components/loading.tsx`
- Route loading with shell: `SiteRouteLoading` in `app/components/loading.tsx`

## Route loading (`loading.tsx`)

Spinner goes in the **content area only** — keep `SiteHeader` and `SiteFooter` visible.

**Standard routes** (no shared layout with header/footer):

```typescript
import { SiteRouteLoading } from "@/app/components/loading";

export default function Loading() {
  return <SiteRouteLoading />;
}
```

**Admin panel routes** (`app/admin-panel/layout.tsx` already renders header, nav, footer):

```typescript
import { PageLoading } from "@/app/components/loading";

export default function Loading() {
  return <PageLoading />;
}
```

Optional custom label: `<SiteRouteLoading label="Loading archive…" />`.

## Suspense fallbacks

```typescript
import { PageLoading, LoadingSpinner } from "@/app/components/loading";

// Full section
<Suspense fallback={<PageLoading />}>

// Inline (buttons, small panels)
<Suspense fallback={<LoadingSpinner size="sm" />}>
```

## Button / action loading

Disable the control and show `LoadingSpinner size="sm"` beside the label, or swap label to `"Loading…"`. Reuse `LoadingSpinner` — do not add one-off CSS spinners.

## Avoid

```typescript
// BAD — skeleton route loaders
export function HomeLoadingSkeleton() { ... }

// BAD — custom spinners
<div className="animate-spin border-4 ..." />

// BAD — no feedback while navigating
export default function Loading() {
  return null;
}
```

`Skeleton` / pulse placeholders are not used for loading states in this app.
